version: 1
display_name: PHTN-50-000267 - The Photon operating system must be configured to use the pam_deny.so module.
global_description: |-
  By requiring the use of the pam_deny.so module, any authentication attempt that does not explicitly succeed with a previous PAM module will be denied. This ensures that no unhandled or ambiguous authentication paths allow unintended access, thereby enforcing a fail-safe mechanism against unauthorised system logins.
osfinger:
  - VMware Photon OS-5
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - PHTN-50-000267
  srg:
    - SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227
  cci:
    - CCI-000366
  nist:
    - CM-6 b
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_photon_5:
    type: custom
    desc: The Photon operating system must be configured to use the pam_deny.so module.
    control_id: PHTN-50-000267
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      At the command line, run the following commands to verify the pam_deny.so module is used:

      # grep '^auth' /etc/pam.d/system-auth

      Example result:

      auth required pam_faillock.so preauth
      auth sufficient pam_unix.so
      auth required pam_faillock.so authfail
      auth optional pam_faildelay.so delay=4000000
      auth required pam_deny.so

      If the pam_deny.so module is not present, or is not configured as the last auth entry, this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      By requiring the use of the pam_deny.so module, any authentication attempt that does not explicitly succeed with a previous PAM module will be denied. This ensures that no unhandled or ambiguous authentication paths allow unintended access, thereby enforcing a fail-safe mechanism against unauthorised system logins.
    remediation: |-
      Navigate to and open:

      /etc/pam.d/system-auth

      Add or update the following lines making sure it is present as the last auth entry:

      auth required pam_deny.so
